  "insights": {
    "title": "Insights on Children Aged 12 to 23 Months - BCG, HepB (birth dose), MMR 1",
    "subtitle": "Key patterns in early-dose and first-dose vaccine coverage by region and background characteristics.",
    "overview": "Coverage improved nationally from 2022 to 2025 for all three vaccines, with the largest national gain in MMR 1. BCG rose from 87.8 to 93.5, HepB (birth dose) from 82.2 to 88.7, and MMR 1 from 79.2 to 89.6. The main concern is not national level but unevenness: some regions are near universal coverage while others, especially BARMM and parts of Mindanao, remain far lower, particularly for HepB birth dose and MMR 1.",
    "sections": [
      {
        "heading": "A clear national improvement, with MMR 1 catching up fastest",
        "body": "All three indicators improved between 2022 and 2025, but MMR 1 moved the most at the national level. The increase for MMR 1 is about 10 points, compared with about 6 points for BCG and HepB birth dose. Even after these gains, HepB and MMR remain below BCG nationally, which suggests the birth dose and later first-dose completion still need closer attention than BCG alone."
      },
      {
        "heading": "Regional gaps remain wide despite high national averages",
        "body": "In 2025, top-performing regions are clustered near the high 90s for all three vaccines, while lower-performing regions sit much further back. BARMM is lowest across BCG (66.3), HepB birth dose (55.6), and MMR 1 (47.8). Zamboanga Peninsula and Northern Mindanao are also in the lower band, and CAR is notably low relative to its 2022 position. This spread shows why national totals alone can overstate how evenly protection is distributed."
      },
      {
        "heading": "Regional change is mixed, with strong gains and clear slippages",
        "body": "Some regions posted sharp gains, including Davao Region for MMR 1 and BARMM from a very low base across all three vaccines. At the same time, CAR shows large declines from 2022 to 2025 in BCG, HepB birth dose, and MMR 1, and Zamboanga Peninsula remains weak on HepB and MMR. The data therefore point to both catch-up and backsliding across regions, not a uniform national trajectory."
      },
      {
        "heading": "Vaccination-card status is a major separator",
        "body": "Children with cards seen have near-universal coverage in 2025 (99.2 for BCG, 92.8 for HepB, 95.8 for MMR 1). Coverage drops among children whose cards are not seen, and falls much further among children who never had a card (47.3 for BCG, 42.6 for HepB, 42.3 for MMR 1). This is one of the strongest divides in the page and should be read as a core stratifier when interpreting overall coverage."
      },
      {
        "heading": "Birth order and socioeconomic gradients are still visible",
        "body": "Coverage is generally higher at lower birth orders and lower among households with less schooling and lower wealth. In 2025, the lowest wealth quintile and Grades 1-6 education group trail the highest quintile and college group by wide margins, especially for HepB and MMR 1. Sex differences are small, and urban-rural differences are present but not as large as card-status, regional, and wealth/education gaps."
      }
    ],
    "takeaways": [
      "National coverage for BCG, HepB birth dose, and MMR 1 improved from 2022 to 2025, with the largest gain in MMR 1.",
      "Regional inequality remains substantial, with very high coverage in some regions and much lower levels in BARMM, Zamboanga Peninsula, and Northern Mindanao.",
      "Vaccination-card status strongly separates outcomes: children with cards seen are near universal, while children who never had cards remain far behind."
    ]
  }
}
